### 📦 Lesson 1: Variables & Printing

**Variables:** Variables are like boxes that store a value and hold onto it. You can make a variable in Python by first entering a name, then adding `=` to assign it a value. For example:
test_variable = "Hello new coders"


But how can we use the variable? Now we are going to learn how to print statements. We can output anything to our screen using print statements!

To print a simple message, we type:
print("YOUR MESSAGE HERE")

Whatever we type inside those quotation marks will appear on the screen. However, to print a **variable**, we pass the variable name directly into the parentheses *without* quotation marks, like this:
print(test_variable)


Did you notice the difference? If you put quotation marks around your variable name, Python will just print the literal word `test_variable` instead of the message hidden inside the box!

